The Herald JOHANNESBURG. — South Africa’s rand slumped and bonds weakened yesterday after official data showed the economy contracted more sharply than expected in the first quarter. The rand was more than 1 percent weaker at 14,60 per dollar after the figures showing growth nosedived 3,2 percent in January-March compared with the previous three months. Economists had only expected a 1,7 percent contraction. Year-on-year growth in Africa’s most industrialised economy was zero compared with forecasts for growth of 0,7 percent. Bonds also weakened, with the yield on the benchmark 10-year issue up 4 basis points at 8,45 percent following the data release. — Reuters. 